{{Infobox Website | name = Jott and company | type = [[Voicemail]] service | logo = Jott.png | screenshot = | caption = Jott logo | url = {{URL|www.jott.com}} | commercial = Yes | language = English | registration = Required | owner = Jott Networks Inc. | author = John Pollard, Shreedhar Madhavapeddi | launch date = April 2006 | current status = | revenue = }} '''Jott''' was a [[voice-to-text]] transcription service which allowed its users to call a [[toll-free telephone number]] and speak for up to 30 seconds. The speech is then transcribed to text using a combination of software and human transcribers who work in a "sterile environment which also includes medical dictation." The message can be sent back to oneself, turned into a reminder, sent to a contact or group, or sent to a third-party "Jott link" such as LiveJournal. Transcribed messages can be delivered to recipients via email, text message, or both.
Jott was founded in April 2006<ref name="hello">{{cite web |url=http://jotts.typepad.com/jott/2006/08/hello_world.html |title=Think it. Jott it. Do it.: hello world |accessdate=2007-05-17 |date=2006-08-28}}</ref> and gained $5.4 million in venture capital in May 2007.<ref name="seattlepi-venture">{{cite web |url=http://www.seattlepi.com/venture/315302_vc11.html |title=Venture Capital: E-mail by voice -- It's quite a deal |accessdate=2007-05-17 |date=2007-05-10}}</ref> Investors in the firm include Ackerley Partners and Draper Richards.<ref name="nw1">{{cite web|url=http://www.nwinnovation.com/fullstory/0006946.html | title=Interview with John Pollard, CEO of Jott Networks|accessdate=2007-07-18|date=2007-01-08}}</ref>
As of July 14, 2009, the company was purchased by [[Nuance Communications]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jott.com/jott/downloads/july2009-jott-aquired-by-nuance.pdf |title=Home - Jott Messenger |publisher= |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090806034218/http://jott.com/jott/downloads/july2009-jott-aquired-by-nuance.pdf |archivedate=2009-08-06 |df= }}</ref>
On April 4, 2011, it was announced that the Jott.com service would be ending on May 3, allowing the company to instead "focus our voice-to-text service investments on carrier and enterprise distribution".<ref>{{cite web|title=Jott service ending on May 3rd, 2011|url=http://jott.com/jotters/index.php/uncategorized/jott-service-ending-on-may-3rd-2011/|work=jott Blog|publisher=Jott Networks Inc.|accessdate=5 April 2011|author=The Jott Team at Nuance|date=4 April 2011|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110406033114/http://jott.com/jotters/index.php/uncategorized/jott-service-ending-on-may-3rd-2011/|archivedate=6 April 2011|df=}}</ref>
